    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I agree that it is painful to build gRPC C++ on windows, but at the same time it is not true that we are building it for every test run on our testing infrastructure.  We do build C core on windows, which is pretty trivial compared to C++ and can be done in visual studio (and by other means) - so we don't have any secret sauce (btw, all the scripts that run our tests are public in our repository so that's not even possible)\r\n\r\nCurrently, building C++ on windows is a bit experimental (it works, but we haven't put together all the pieces to make it pleasant and simple to build).\r\nI think the right plan here is to:\r\n1. make C++ easily buildable on windows (the problem is mostly the openssl and protobuf integration).\r\n2. document it properly\r\n3. (publishing artifacts is optional - because everyone can build them as easily. Also it is not clear that the artifacts would be usable by everyone based on the compiler and linker options)."
  },
